<p>Draw a triangle <em>ABC</em> and pick a point <em>V</em> that&#8217;s not on one of its sides. Draw a segment from each of the triangle&#8217;s vertices through <em>V</em>. Now draw a new triangle whose sides are parallel to these three segments. Segments drawn from each of this new triangle&#8217;s vertices and parallel to the first triangle&#8217;s sides, as shown, will meet in a common point.</p>
<p>Proven by James Clerk Maxwell!</p>
